Civil rights group warns against traveling to Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) has warned black people traveling to Missouri against the state's discriminatory policies and racist attacks.
The statement reads: “The NAACP travel note for the state of Missouri, valid until August 28, 2017, calls on all African-American travelers, visitors and Missouri residents to be extra vigilant and extremely cautious when moving around the state, given the suspicious racial events that have recently taken place across the state.”
According to the NAACP, the group was urged to issue travel warnings both by the recent Missouri law, which makes it harder to win lawsuits for discrimination, and by the fact that minorities are inequally targeted by state law enforcement.
“People’s civil rights are being violated.
They are pulled to the edge of the road because of their skin color, they are beaten or killed,” Rod Chapel, president of the NAACP Missouri branch, told The Kansas City Star.
"We've never received complaints so heavily."
This is the first such warning issued by the organization for the state of the United States.
The group referred to events such as racist insults against black students at the University of Missouri and the death of 28-year-old black Tory Sanders from Tennessee.
Sanders died in suspicious circumstances early this year after he ran out of gas while driving through the state and was arrested by the Missouri police without being charged with a crime.
In addition, the note refers to a recent report by the Missouri Chief Prosecutor, which shows that black drivers in the state are 75% more likely to be stopped than white drivers.
"The note is meant to make people aware and warn their families, friends and colleagues about what could happen in Missouri," Chapel said.
“People need to be ready, whether it’s taking bail money or informing relatives that they’re crossing the state.”
Based on the latest data from the FBI’s Hate Crime Reporting Program, 100 hate crimes were documented in Missouri in 2015, placing the state in the 16th place across the state in terms of the number of similar offenses.
A travel warning is also a response to a new Missouri law that makes it harder for a company to sue for discrimination in search of housing or work.
The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) had previously issued travel notes for Texas and Arizona after these states passed immigration laws that required local authorities to arrest people for immigration violations, as ACLU said it would increase racial profiling.
Usually, travel warnings are issued by the State Department about other countries, but recently interest groups have begun to use this measure as a counter-reaction to certain U.S. laws and trends.
Hepatitis: What can anyone know about the different forms of this serious disease?
Hepatitis, or inflammation of the liver, can be caused by five different hepatitis viruses - A, B, C, D and E.
All these viruses provoke acute inflammation of liver tissue.
Chronic hepatitis B and C, however, can develop into liver cirrhosis, or wrinkle, and liver cancer.
Kuluo Kutsar, the epidemiology advisor at the Health Board, says that the symptoms of acute hepatitis are the same for all types of inflammation of the liver - fever, fatigue, loss of appetite, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, grayish stools, dark urine, muscle and joint pain, and yellowing of the skin and mucous membranes.
The last sign of the disease also derives from the popular name jaundice.
In children, hepatitis can pass without symptoms.
Various types of inflammation of the liver can be determined only on the basis of data from a laboratory study.
Acute hepatitis can transition to chronic hepatitis and go on for decades without symptoms of the disease, which means that a person may not know anything about his dangerous liver-damaging disease.
Hearing Kutsar highlights the various forms of hepatitis and describes their course in more detail.
Hepatitis A viruses spread from a sick person and infect us by eating contaminated food or drinking water, sex, stool from an infected person to hands and hands, food, surfaces, objects, getting into the mouth, and drug use.
Persons at risk of contracting hepatitis A include family members and carers, people with chronic liver disease, people who have sex with an infected person, men who have sex with men, drug addicts, travellers who visit countries with high prevalence of hepatitis A.
Vaccinations can be used to prevent infection, especially for people who travel a lot and are at risk of hepatitis A.
In addition, daily hygiene requirements are important: wash or disinfect your hands, wash all fruits and vegetables before using them for food.
Hepatitis B viruses are transmitted by contact with the blood of a sick person, by injecting drugs, tattooing, piercing, using blood-contaminated household items (toothbrushes, shaving products), by having sex with a donor, with a person suspected of having hepatitis, and from a hepatitis disease mother to a fetus/newborn.
The risk group for hepatitis B infection includes injecting drug addicts, sex partners of infected people, men having sex with men, newborns of infected mothers, family members and carers of sick people, health care workers, rescue workers and police officers exposed to blood and other body fluids, and travellers visiting countries with high levels of hepatitis B disease.
It is possible to vaccinate people to prevent hepatitis B; in particular, it is recommended to vaccinate people at risk, as well as people with chronic liver disease, HIV infection, sexually transmitted diseases and diabetes.
Other preventive measures for hepatitis B include: refraining from using foreign hygiene and manicure equipment, other sharps and needles, tattooing and piercing, and using condoms for infectious sex or avoiding sexual risk behaviour.
Vaccination against hepatitis B is part of the national immunisation programme in Estonia and is free for children.
Hepatitis C viruses are transmitted through contact with the blood of a sick person, drug injections, tattooing, piercing, using blood-contaminated domestic objects, donor blood, having sex with a person suspected of having hepatitis, and from a hepatitis mother to a fetus/newborn.
The risk group for hepatitis C infection includes injecting drug users, sex partners of infected people, men having sex with men, newborns of infected mothers, family members and carers of sick people, health care workers and rescue workers exposed to blood and other body fluids, people living with HIV, and travellers visiting countries with high levels of hepatitis C infection.
The preventive measures for hepatitis C include: refraining from using foreign hygiene and manicure equipment, other sharps and needles, tattooing and piercing, and using a condom for infectious sex.
There is no vaccine against hepatitis C.
D hepatitis is caused by the hepatitis D virus, which reproduces in the presence of the hepatitis B virus.
Therefore, hepatitis D infection occurs with hepatitis B or as a superinfection in patients with chronic hepatitis B.
D hepatitis viruses are transmitted through contact with blood and other body fluids, syringes and needles contaminated with them, sexually, and rarely from infected mothers to fetuses.
The risk group for hepatitis D is chronic carriers of the hepatitis B virus and people without immunity against hepatitis B.
An effective preventive measure is vaccination with the hepatitis B vaccine, which also protects a person from infection with the hepatitis D virus.
Hepatitis E viruses are spread via faecal-oral routes through drinking water and food, including eating little heat-treated beef, fish and shellfish, donor blood, shared syringes, and infected mother to fetus.
Travelers can become infected with hepatitis E in countries with a high incidence of hepatitis E.
Preventive measures for hepatitis E include compliance with hygiene requirements: wash or disinfect your hands after going to the toilet, before cooking and eating, after caring for the sick.
Fruits and vegetables should be washed before consumption, avoid eating little heat-treated beef, fish and seafood, drink only safe drinking water, and refrain from using drugs.
