Blocking critics from Facebook Do not apply for state office if you can’t stand the criticism of voters
The father of our country knew a lot about unfavourable media coverage.
The Americans loved George Washington, but it didn’t take long for the newspapers to stigmatize him for everything from internal politics to his policies.
Criticism, of course, annoyed him.
But he did not keep his critics silent.
In 1783, Washington said, “Freedom of speech may be deprived of us, and we may be led, in silence and silence, to slaughter like sheep.”
It brings me to the Governor of Maryland, Larry Hogan, who has to work hard to be more like Washington.
Hogan’s subordinates have blocked and deleted posts from at least 450 people who posted their opinions on his official Facebook page.
Earlier this week, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) filed a lawsuit against him.
The governor's officials stamped the lawsuit as null and void, and the online comments were full of counter-reactions in the style of "Who cares?".
"It's just Facebook," many said.
But it does.
And it matters a lot when it comes to a man like Hogan.
This is a remarkably popular Republican governor in a predominantly democratic state.
He ranks second-best among the 50 governors of the country.
Hogan is not an unthinkingly responsive noisy head.
He has led the state with a firm hand and has remained firmly committed to his principles.
In addition, he has used Facebook quite aptly as the main tool for communicating with his voters, for example, presenting his bald head cheerfully for the first time after chemotherapy.
Thus, blocking people visiting the Governor’s page, which is an officially labeled public forum, managed by staff who receive dollars from taxpayers, is unnecessary and ultimately dangerous.
Hogan spokeswoman Amelia Chasse defended the governor’s behavior in an interview with The Washington Post, arguing that blocking comments was nothing more than moderation.
But it’s too easy to paint a picture of online slanderous Internet trolls, spammers or hateful people.
The Post talked to a number of real people who Hogan blocked.
And that's exactly what they're real people communicating with their chosen leaders. Teacher, business owner and pastor, not internet trolls.
They all said their comments were respectful, thoughtful and not obscene.
The pastor quoted the Bible in his post, stressing Hogan’s Catholicism.
Lawyer Lakshmi Sarma Raman, from Bowie, Maryland, did not incite hatred, but genuine hate crimes.
"I politely commented that I was disappointed that he has not responded to hate crimes or other recent news," he wrote in a commentary on The Post news story.
“I also don’t like the idea that when a lot of people comment on the same topic, someone immediately indifferently calls it a collective effort, rather than admitting that there are a lot of concerned citizens.”
What the governor’s officials called a “directed spam attack,” others would probably call “public support.”
The Facebook era allows you to easily match messages by simply blocking a critic or deleting a negative comment.
It is much cleaner than in the old days, when workers had to be sent out to do the same, to gather up newspapers with critical editorials and burn them or arrest protesters and make them remain silent.
But that’s exactly what’s happening right now, just digitally.
Hogan is not the first government official to be criticized for denying Facebook and other social media channels.
President Trump has been sued by Twitter users who have been blocked from his Twitter feed.
One of the first significant judgments on this issue was made last week in Virginia.
U.S. District Judge James C. Cacheris in Alexandria ruled that the chairman of the Loudoun County Oversight Board violated the First Amendment by blocking a voter from her Facebook page.
In Kentucky, ACLU also visited Governor Matt Bevin (R) after using Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be that hard.
At the time of Washington, affordable postage costs had a similar effect to the Internet.
Between 1776 and 1800, the number of newspapers quadrupled, and anonymous writers overturned his way of managing.
And even then, Washington had to deal with anonymous trolls.
People wrote letters to newspapers under pseudonyms such as Juricola, Valerius, Belisarius, and Portius, putting Washington’s decisions to the ground.
According to historical documents collected as part of an online letter collection project by George Washington, his office was buried under petitions that criticized his views on friendship, trade, and shipping treaties with the United Kingdom.
But he didn’t keep them quiet.
Freedom of expression, dissent and debate are the foundations of our country.
And proper management means accepting it.
