Poverty and Death in the Gold Land of Indonesia
When Bardina Degei prepares dinner, she doesn't use the stove.
He seldom even uses the pot.
In a wooden cabin in Enarotali, the capital of the regent of Paniai in the revolting province of Papua, Indonesia, the housewife places a sweet potato, called nota, directly on the fire.
After half an hour, the charred tuber is removed from the fire and eagerly injected into the skin with unwashed hands.
Degei sits on a muddy floor without any furniture, and there he also does his daily household chores, such as washing his laundry with cloudy water from a nearby swamp.
The role of a toilet is played by a bucket in an unroofed room.
Since she is the youngest of her husband’s four wives, she is not assigned to take care of any field.
Polygamy is common here.
Working late can be dangerous, however, most of the men in the village are unemployed and many of them drink heavily, and there are also soldiers here.
“No one has the courage to visit after 5 p.m.,” he said.
This is a rare glimpse of life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed by Indonesia in 1969 after a controversial referendum in which only 1,026 elderly people were forced to vote in front of the occupying forces.
The movement that prompted liberation from Dutch domination quickly turned its rage against the Jakarta government, which still holds the region in its strong control, excluding foreign journalists and human rights watchdogs.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and Western Papua, leaving the eastern part of the independent Papua New Guinea.
Enarotali is both a remote and abandoned place. To get there, you have to fly from the provincial capital, Jayapura, to Nabire in 90 minutes, and then take a five-hour drive with a rental car to make you nauseous.
There is no public transport.
With a population of about 19,000, the city consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences and covered by corrugated iron roofs, the rust of which has turned different shades into yellow-brown.
Very few Indonesians have made the journey here, not to mention journalists, and almost no foreigners have come here.
Before the arrival of Christian missionaries, the Mee Pago papayas worshipped a god named Uga Tamee.
There were other changes as well.
"We weren't used to wearing such clothes," says Degei, referring to his colorful hand-woven turban, dark blouse, and vivid skirt.
"Before that, we only wore leaves on the body."
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, with 28% of the population living below the poverty line, and statistics on infant mortality and illiteracy are among the worst in Asia.
But it is also a gold-rich country in Indonesia.
Just 100 kilometers from Pania, a mountainous province of about 153,000 people in New Jersey, lies the world's largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Freeport McMoran, a company based in Phoenix.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined about <0x24>3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua can boast of commercial timber stocks estimated at USD 78 billion.
But these riches are the source of suffering for the Papuans, as they result in the stifling presence of the powerful Indonesian army.
A 2005 study in The New York Times showed that Freeport paid approximately <0x24>20 million to local military personnel and units between 1998 and 2004, including up to <0x24>150,000 to one officer.
This golden geese is threatened and ruthlessly dealt with by the Papuans in their quest for greater autonomy.
According to human rights activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian army.
According to the Asian Human Rights Commission, in the highlands of Papuan tribes, mass killings to the extent of genocide occurred in the 1970s.
Last year alone, more than 3,900 peaceful protesters were arrested in the Indonesian police area.
The 2016 report by the Archdiocese of Birsbane, entitled "We Lose Everything", contains testimony to atrocities committed in the previous year, such as extrajudicial executions, torture (according to another report, rape and electric shocks are particularly common) and brutal repression of peaceful demonstrations.
“It’s hard to count the number of victims because such incidents happen every week,” said Human Rights Watch Indonesian researcher Andreas Harsono.
The screws have been tightened even harder, as Papua’s natural resources have caused an influx of settlers from other parts of Indonesia.
83% of the province’s 3.5 million inhabitants are Christians, but demographics are changing as Muslim economic migrants arrive from Indonesia’s crowded islands of Java, Kalimantan, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese family diners sell crispy chicken and mixed vegetables gado-gado, which is served with peanut sauce.
The locals can't compete with them.
“Migrants started selling chicken and vegetables on the traditional market cheaper than local papayas,” explains Abeth You, a 24-year-old born in Paniai, who moved to Jayapura, the provincial capital for work.
"The indigenous Papuan mama-mama's [women] will lose their market share as a result."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, known among the people as Jokowi, promised in his 2014 election campaign to address these inequalities and human rights violations in Papua.
On his way to the presidential palace in Jakarta, the former carpenter won 27 of the 29 electoral districts of Papua, including Paniai.
But very little has changed in Papua, and the locals feel betrayed.
"Our hearts are broken because in 2014 we voted for Jokow in anticipation that he would fulfill our hopes for restoring justice," You said.
In fact, only two months after Jokowi took office in October, Paniai was in a low position.
On December 7, 2014, 11 children in Enarotal were singing Christmas songs by a fire when two Indonesian soldiers came out of the dark on a motorcycle.
The kids told them to turn on the headlights.
According to local pastor Yavedt Tebai, one of the soldiers was offended by their tone of voice and later returned with four soldiers.
According to the victims and witnesses, the drunken soldiers chased the children and beat them with the handles of their rifles.
Then one of the soldiers fired on the children.
One child, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was so brutally beaten that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, the nearby electoral commission building was set on fire, and the next day things escalated even further.
Approximately 1,000 young Papuan men, women and children gathered to demand justice on the football field in front of the local police station and military command center.
They wore ceremonial hunting booths and performed a waita dance of the papua honey pago tribe, during which they ran around and imitated the bird song.
Some protesters began throwing stones at police and military personnel.
In the wake of the escalation of resentment, the soldiers were sent an order through the internal radio: "If the crowd is more than three times resisting, shoot them," according to an official document seen in TIME magazine, but not released to local media.
Yeremias Kayame (56), an elder in the Kego Koto district of Enarotali, felt the threat and called for peace, asking the crowd to return home.
No one wanted to listen.
"When I turned around, I was suddenly shot in my left wrist," he told TIME magazine in his bright colors on the porch of a wooden house.
Kayame still doesn't know who the shooter was, but says the bullet came from the ranks of assembled soldiers.
"There was a lot of people, a lot of gunshots," he added.
Local man Alfius Youw was shot three times, according to his cousin.
"I ran to him and examined his body to make sure it was him," Yohanes told TIME, who, like many Indonesians, uses only one name.
"I saw him dead... I kissed him."
Papua Police Chief Inspector Yotje Mende told reporters that his subordinates only returned to the security of their station because it was attacked.
"We must defend ourselves if we are threatened with death," said Commissioner Pudjo Sulistiyo, a spokesman for the Papuan police in 2015.
“It’s a matter of life and death.”
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many injured.
The news of the killings did not reach Jakarta until the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi gave a passionate speech in Jayapura, expressing his condolences to the families of the victims and promising to deal with the abuses in Papua.
"I want this case resolved immediately so that it never happens again in the future," he said.
In October 2016, Minister of Security Wiranto announced that he would put in place an extrajudicial mechanism to resolve the violations of human rights committed.
Almost immediately an apology followed.
“Most crimes happened a long time ago.
Some of them occurred in the 1990s and early 2000s.
The point is that we are committed to resolving these crimes, but we have to follow certain processes,” he said.
Speaking to TIME magazine in Jakarta on June 5, however, Wiranto withdrew his words, saying that he had no intention of creating a mechanism in Papua to deal with complaints.
Instead, he said, “Everything will be judged by the law.”
Wiranto, who has been accused by the UN of crimes against human rights in connection with the deaths of more than 1,000 people in East Timor during the bloody independence referendum in 1999, said 11 human rights violations in Papua had already been resolved, including the one in Paniai.
The families of Paniai’s victims accepted such claims with deep mistrust.
"I've been interrogated four times in the last three years, but no progress has been made," Yohanes said.
"I'm tired."
He said he was still scared years later.
"I'm scared," he says.
"I'm afraid the military will arrest me, I'm afraid I'll be shot."
His brother Yacobus confirmed the opinion that the Paniai people are afraid to autopsy the incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after helping to bury four of the victims.
"After the bodies were buried, the army came looking for me," he says.
The shootings have not stopped.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police shot villagers in the neighbouring Paniai regiment in Deiyai.
One person was killed and 17 wounded, including children, when a quarrel broke out between villagers and the manager of a construction company who refused to transport the unconscious man to the hospital.
This man, 24-year-old Ravianus Douw, who drowned fishing in a nearby river, died on the way to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested in front of the company’s office on the construction site.
According to police, the villagers threw stones at the police officers, and the latter responded with warning shots.
But locals say a mobile brigade (Indonesian military police) started shooting at the people, killing one person.
"We were in a big panic, we're afraid of revenge," said Dominggu Badii, a 29-year-old who lives near the hospital and saw the wounded being recorded.
"I've been hiding in my house for two days."
The Deiyai Parliament has called for the prosecution of the police involved and the withdrawal of the police's mobile brigade from the area.
Paniai has always been a problem for the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development feeds the dissatisfaction of the honey, moni, dan and damali tribes living in the greening highlands of Papua.
Many of them have joined the rebel army of the Free Papua Movement (VPL), which claims to defend the rights of the Papuans by organising random attacks and abductions among Indonesian soldiers.
Some of the leaders of the VPL come from Pania, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
In response, the military, under the pretext of 'protecting national sovereignty', has in recent years arrested and arbitrarily detained thousands of people in Paniai.
Some of them will never show up again.
Among the people of Papua, Pania is known as the "tragically forgotten place".
Poverty feeds dissatisfaction.
The small amount of rice sold in Enarotal is too expensive for the locals to buy.
Bread is just as inaccessible.
People grow all their own food mainly from sweet potatoes, along with a little fruit and leafy vegetables.
Farming is the work of women, each of whom can care for four or five sweet potato fields.
They usually keep most of the harvest for the family, the rest is sold on the local market.
Ten sweet potatoes cost only 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Over time, economic inequalities have worsened between indigenous Papuans and new migrants, who have arrived in large numbers since the opening of new routes at Nabire Airport.
The few jobs that exist go to better-educated and wealthier migrants.
Papua itself often lacks the capital or the necessary skills to run a competitive business.
"Young people are not interested in staying because there are no jobs or money here," said John Gobai, chairman of the Paniai Tribe Council.
Separation keeps the world's eyes away from Papua.
In addition, there are severe restrictions on foreign media.
Earlier this year, French journalists Franck Escudie and Basille Longchamp were expelled from Papua because they “did not follow appropriate practices” despite being granted rare filming licenses.
According to Phelim Kine, deputy head of Human Rights Watch Asia, Jokow’s election promises to lift restrictions on reporting to promote transparency and development have not been fulfilled.
"Journalists trying to report in the most troubled provinces of Papua in the east and Western Papua in Indonesia are facing new threats of visa rejection and blacklisting," he said in a statement.
The lack of a journalistic look means that international pressure on the Indonesian government is largely confined to Papua’s immediate neighbours.
In March, the United Nations Human Rights Council urged the six Pacific states Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, Marshall Islands and Solomon Islands to investigate “a variety of large-scale crimes” in Papua, including the Paniai shooting.
These same countries have historically supported the VPL as well.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Arrmanatha Nasir dismissed the group's allegations, saying to journalists in Jakarta: "Democratic order and freedom of the press still exist in Indonesia, so it would be difficult to bury evidence of human rights violations."
The local people want more foreign governments to be noticed.
When the Dutch official delegation, led by the country's human rights ambassador Kees Van Bar, visited Jayapura on 4 May, local people who attended the meeting but wanted to remain anonymous interrupted their silence, according to a source, urging: "We want freedom."
There will be a new presidential election in Indonesia in 2019, but the Papuans do not believe they will vote for Jokowi again.
"Jokowi is a man of good intentions, but he is surrounded by people involved in the shooting of Paniai," said Hobai, chairman of the Tribal Council.
He wants Jokow to understand that, in addition to living under the threat of a predatory army, the Paniai people are suffering because of niggas’ education and health services.
According to Gobai, the people of Paniai, like the rest of the Papuans, regard their vote given to Jokow as a debt that he has to pay.
"They don't need money, they want justice," he said.
Despite threats and intimidation, the families of the Paniai shooting victims survived the last symbolic uprising and buried the body of one of the victims in the land opposite the police station and military base.
Knowing that justice may never be put on its feet, they will at least not allow those responsible to forget their crimes.
"One of our family members was killed," Yacobus says with his head down.
"What else can we do?"
