The EPA annulled the decision to postpone the smog order after the lawsuits
The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) revoked the decision to delay the adoption of a Obama-era decree that obliges states to limit emissions of smog one day after 15 states sued the agency for this action.
The EPA announced its decision to resume “2015 ozone determination procedures” late on Wednesday, saying it shows the agency’s commitment to working with the states.
"We believe we need to have a dialogue with our state-based partners and listen to them," EPA chief Scott Pruitt said in a statement.
Pruitt had announced in June the EPA's intention to postpone ozone measurements to measure smog pollution in different parts of the country, in order to determine where its level should be reduced by one year until October 2018 in order to meet the stricter air quality standards.
The 15 mostly democratic states filed lawsuits with the District of Columbia on Tuesday, claiming that the decision was illegal.
President Donald Trump’s administration has tried to pull back a number of environmental regulations imposed by former President Barack Obama. According to Trump, this is part of a more comprehensive plan to boost economic growth.
But these aspirations have provoked counter-reactions among Democrats and nature conservation groups concerned about the impact of increased pollutants on human health.
According to the EPA website, inhaling ozone-containing air “can reduce lung function and increase the risk of respiratory diseases such as asthma.”
