Which corners of the world are moving to Estonia?
Last year, the Police and Border Guard Board (PPA) extended and issued a record number of more than 13,000 residence permits to third-country nationals who have mostly travelled to Estonia for work, study or family visits.
For example, if last year it was decided to issue a temporary residence permit to 6,702 aliens, then last year the number was 4,928.
The authorities cannot say how many immigrants will eventually remain permanently in Estonia, but such an analysis is being prepared by the Ministry of the Interior.
Ten years ago, nearly 500 Ukrainians moved to Estonia each year, but in recent years, this number is approaching 2,000.
The number of applicants for residence permits increased exponentially during the crisis in Ukraine - in 2014 1087 people received temporary residence permits, a year earlier 675.
According to Statistics Estonia, the number of Ukrainian citizens is growing the most in Estonia - 850 Ukrainian citizens arrived in Estonia last year more than they left.
“The Ukrainian community has always been large in Estonia, and because of the difficult circumstances in the country, it is natural that people are looking for work and learning opportunities in a country where the community and many families are already in front of them,” said Kristin Rammus, a spokeswoman for the Ministry of the Interior.
Last year and last year, the number of Ukrainians who received temporary residence permits was even higher than the number of Russian citizens, even though the latter had the highest number of temporary residence permits issued in the last ten years.
While Ukrainians come here mostly to work, Russian citizens come here for family migration.
"Given the historical Russian community here, they are also likely to have the greatest family ties with people living in Russia," said Helina Maasing, a migration researcher at the National Defence Academy.
“When we look at where Russian citizens who have obtained Estonian residence permits have moved to, there is Ida-Virumaa immediately after Harjumaa,” he added and pointed out that about 40 per cent of them have married a citizen of the European Union.
Last year, 1696 Russian citizens were granted temporary residence permits, which is also a record number.
At the same time, the number of Russians who wished to extend their residence permit decreased.
"The reason for the leap is that instead of extending the residence permit, a new residence permit has been applied for permanently to settle in Estonia," said Rammus, a spokesman for the Ministry of the Interior, according to whom the interest of Russian citizens in the Estonian residence permit has remained stable for years.
Foreigners who have resided here for at least three years can apply for a new residence permit for permanent residence in Estonia from the previous year.
Its purpose is to encourage adapted people to stay here.
A residence permit for long-term residents, for example, requires five years.
The extension of the old residence permit has also been reduced due to the new residence permit.
Last year, for example, 146 Ukrainians who have worked here for at least three years were granted such a residence permit.
Now Ukrainians can change jobs, and the Estonian state is no longer keeping a finger on whether the wage criterion is met.
This residence permit became very popular last year - applicants were still grey passport holders (1029), Russians (487), Indians (54), and Nigerians (36).
Altogether, 1968 people received residence permits to settle in Estonia, including 23 Americans, 12 Egyptians, 18 Georgians and the same number of Chinese.
In the first half of this year, the total number of such applicants is already 1269.
Within ten years, Nigeria has surprisingly become a country whose citizens are among the most active applicants for Estonian residence permits.
When Nigerians received three residence permits in 2007, last year they received 200.
They come from Nigeria to study in these universities.
Estonian higher education institutions are also popular among Georgians, Chinese and Turks, for example.
The number of Indian, Bangladeshi and Nigerian citizens has increased mainly due to study migration.
The rule is that wherever a community has emerged, it is easier for others to come,” Rammus added.
In the last ten years, two people have also moved to Estonia from, for example, North Korea, as much from Laos and Madagascar.
Ten people have come here from Cuba, 231 from South Korea, 40 from Indonesia and four from Uruguay.
When around 6,000 third-country nationals are granted a residence permit per year, this is about 0.46% of the total population.
Even if we add the citizens of the European Union, migration remains at about a percentage," Maasing said.
