New results of tests to assess the age of Swedish asylum seekers have been published
In Sweden, asylum seekers were tested for their age with a novel medical approach. The latest results show that more than 80 percent of those tested were rated older than 18, but not everyone believes the results are accurate.
The Swedish National Institute of Forensic Medicine (Rättsmedicinalverket) started testing early this year.
The tests were created to better estimate the age of asylum seekers after the Swedish Migrationsverket was criticised for failing to correctly determine the age of a number of allegedly minor refugees.
To date, Migrationsverket has sent 6,880 cases for testing and the Institute of Forensic Medicine has issued a total of 2,481 test results between mid-March and 31 July 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) were rated to be 18 years of age or older, and in another 25 cases, the Forensics Institute estimated that the test subject “may be 18 years of age or older.”
In 432 cases, it was concluded that a person was "probably younger than 18".
Tests are only used if the age of the person is questionable.
According to Johan Göransson, who works at the Institute of Forensic Medicine, the results are consistent with those of the previous months.
“We don’t see a big difference compared to last month’s statistics, the numbers are pretty consistent,” he told The Local.
The fact that a large number of cases were estimated to be over 18 does not necessarily mean that asylum seekers have lied about their age.
In May, the Institute issued 581 test results and said that in 442 cases, "there are indications that the subject is 18 years of age or older."
But when the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet looked at the results of these 581 tests, it turned out that in 243 cases the person had directly claimed to be 18 this year.
This medical age-assessment method, which uses X-rays of wisdom teeth and MRI of knee joints, to be analysed by dentists and radiologists, has been criticized in some circles.
One of the skeptics is endocrinologist Claude Marcus of the Karolinska Institutet, whose work includes assessing the biological maturity of people to find out if they went through puberty sooner or later than usual.
“I’ve had reason to think about it and I don’t think the measurement method used today should be used.
Determining the biological age in this way is very uncertain.
"If we can't say for sure, we shouldn't pretend we can," he told Metro.
But Johan Göransson of the Institute of Forensic Medicine defended the accuracy of the tests: "Overall, it can be said that the risk of a child being categorized inaccurately into an adult is low.
The highest risk, perhaps at about 10%, is when a person is slightly under 18.
