The electric car revolution is changing the demand for metals.
Who are the winners and losers?
Not only will the electric car revolution significantly change everything from fuel to infrastructure, it will also create new winners and losers in the metal market.
While mining giants like Glencore can say that they win in one place and lose in another, smaller mining companies won’t be helped.
Today, Glencore earns from coal and oil, but in the future, the demand for cobalt, lithium, copper, aluminium and nickel will grow in the era of electric cars.
This year, the governments of the UK, France and Norway have decided to ban the sale of new cars using fossil fuels in the coming decades.
That’s why Volvo has already announced that they plan to abandon the internal combustion engine, and Tesla is launching a cheaper Model 3 electric car.
According to Bloomberg New Energy Finance, more electric cars will be sold than oil-fuelled cars in the next two decades.
"In terms of some metals, it changes everything," Simona Gambranini, a raw material analyst at Capital Economics, told Bloomberg.
We have already seen a major impact on metals such as cobalt and lithium, for which demand has been growing for years.
Electric cars have about three times more copper than conventional cars, Glencore said.
Even more copper is needed at charging stations, which Exane BNP Paribas estimates will increase copper demand by about five percent by 2025.
Increasing demand for electric car batteries means additional demand for lithium, cobalt, graphite and manganese.
Glencore will benefit from a growing trend in electric cars, from rising copper prices and from being the world’s largest cobalt producer, Jefferies Group predicted.
The other winners of the electric car race are Freeport-McMoRan and First Quantum Minerals.
The market is already responding to a changing trend.
Cobalt prices on the London Metal Exchange have risen 70 percent this year.
The price increase last year was 37 percent.
Copper has also increased by 14% this year, mainly due to economic growth.
Glencore’s stock in London rose by 20 percent, surpassing rivals Rio Tinto Group, BHP Billiton and Anglo American.
On the side of the losers, lead companies like Recycling and Campine will have to adapt to a new era.
The main end-use of lead are batteries that power the starters of petrol and diesel cars.
Electric cars use lithium-ion batteries.
"This is a serious risk to lead demand unless another purpose is found to overcome the decline in demand," said Michael Widmer, head of metal market analysis at Bank of America Merrill Lynch.
Lead price movements have not yet seen the impact of a rolling trend.
Lead has risen 17 percent this year, making it the best metal in London among the major industrial metals.
Investors will only see problems with metal in the far future.
“I’m not sure it’s that bad for lead because cheap oil keeps ordinary cars in competition,” said Herwig Schmidt, sales manager at Triland Metals.
When the demand for lead drops, it happens slowly.
This may happen in about 10 years.
In the meantime, stricter exhaust standards mean that demand for hybrid cars, which depend on advanced lead-based batteries for frequent engine start-ups, will increase, according to an international lead and zinc research organization.
Light metals such as aluminum replace steel, as lighter cars can drive farther with less electricity.
This explains the additional demand for aluminum mummy of 1.6 million tons between 2013 and 2016.
It accounts for 2.7% of the world’s total aluminium production.
This trend is likely to worsen, Widmer said.
Aluminium has risen by 13 percent this year, as growing demand from car manufacturers has led to a market deficit.
Steel producers don't sleep.
AK Steel Holding is working with General Motors to use nanotechnology to produce ultra-light car bodies.
ArcelorMittal and Tata Steel Europe are also trying to develop a lighter alloy steel to withstand aluminium mummy.
"Strength steel should be the answer to this development," said Sylvain Brunet, an analyst at Exane BNP Paribas.
Some progress has been made in Europe.
The end of the oil age can also bring suffering to platinum.
Last year, about half of this precious metal was spent on catalysts for diesel-powered cars, metal refiner Johnson Matthey said.
"Many currently in high demand raw materials such as oil and platinum may not be in high demand in the future," said Bernard Dahdah, a raw material analyst at Natixis.
This does not mean that raw materials as a whole will become less important, but their importance will change within 15 years.
Platinum manufacturers believe there will be continued demand for diesel hybrid cars.
Uncore chief Marc Grynberg said that by 2025, more hybrid cars will be sold than full-electric cars.
The great hope of platinum manufacturers in the 10-year perspective is that Toyota Motor and Hyundai Motos will develop hydrogen-cell-based cars that rely on platinum to produce electricity from hydrogen.
So far, however, this technology has not proven itself commercially.
"Diesel seems to have a clear loser on its way to electric cars," said Brunet of Paribas, Exane BNP.
German car manufacturers suffered a major setback in July after a Stuttgart court banned the use of diesel in the hometowns of Mercedes-Benz and Porsche.
