NHS to prescribe 10,000 HIV-controversial drugs
Patients will have access to “transformative” HIV-prevention treatment since September after a battle in the Supreme Court over whether the NHS should fund the drug.
The NHS England reported that the National Health Service will now make available an estimated 10,000 pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) tablets to be administered before intercourse during the initial three-year clinical trial, which has shown a reduction in the risk of infection of high-risk people by about 86%.
The NHS agreed to fund a clinical trial after the Court of Appeals supported a ruling by the Supreme Court last year that the NHS was able to pay for PrEP, despite the agency’s own claims that the drug should be financed by local governments instead.
NHS England chief executive Simon Stevens welcomed the move as a “new large-scale intervention,” while the National AIDS Fund (NAT) described it as “a turning point.”
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield are among the first to start registering people. More clinics will be added in October before the program is deployed everywhere in England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a course of HIV medications taken before intercourse to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
The results of clinical trials show that PrEP significantly reduces HIV transmission among people at risk of infection.
Taking PrEP before intercourse means that there is a sufficient amount of certain drugs in the human body that prevent infection with HIV.
Such drugs can be taken every day or no later than two hours before intercourse.
Eligible candidates for treatment include gay or bisexual men, transgender people, and people whose partners are infected with HIV and are not receiving treatment.
Clinics identify suitable people who are willing to participate in the clinical trial, including men, women, transgender people and those whose HIV partner is not receiving antiretroviral therapy.
People who live in England and have chosen a family doctor there can also register their wish to participate at the local sexual health clinic participating in the programme.
The program costs <0xC2><0xA3>10 million and the NHS England signed a contract to receive the drugs this week after an international tender.
The aim of the clinical trial is to assess the real potential of PrEP by collecting clinical evidence about who the drug is intended for and how it is consumed and applied in the big picture.
Stevens said, "This new large-scale intervention should complement and amplify the wide-ranging and increasingly successful fight against the spread of HIV.
This is another milestone in over three decades of fighting one of humanity’s greatest health problems.”
Deborah Gold, executive director of NAT, said: “This is a turning point in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, if properly targeted at those in need and at risk, offers an opportunity to change the HIV epidemic in England.
Since September, high-risk people in England have access to a powerful new tool through this NHS-funded clinical trial, which is individually manageable and not dependent on negotiation with a partner, thereby improving many lives.
We warmly welcome this announcement."
Ian Green, CEO of the Terrence Higgins Foundation, said: “Now it’s a priority to ensure that a clinical trial across the country is put into effect quickly and that none of the people at risk for HIV are left out.
Now that the PrEP clinical trial drug has been procured, we are on our way to protecting more than 10,000 people at risk of contracting HIV.
Public Health Shadow Minister Sharon Hodgson said: “The start of the clinical trial for PrEP is very welcome and very late after months of delays and dragging the government’s legs.
Evidence shows how much this medicine can change the prevention of HIV and stop the spread of this life-changing infection.
This clinical trial takes us one step closer to a complete understanding of the benefits of PrEP.
It is now important for the clinical trial to be deployed across the country as soon as possible to protect people who are exposed to HIV and to take us one step closer to stopping the spread of HIV in society.”
