Trump's new chief of staff plans to limit the president's media consumption.
Others have tried and failed.
Maybe John F. Kelly can do it.
In that case, he would be the first.
The White House’s new chief of staff plans to limit the flow of information, including news, to President Trump, in the hope that it will keep the chief in a flatter water.
Here's a snippet from reporter Josh Dawsey:
“When the new White House Chief of Staff, John F. Kelly, met with senior officials on his first day of work, he highlighted a key issue in President Donald Trump’s White House, which he planned to solve by getting bad information into the president’s hands.
Kelly told officials that information must pass through him, whether on paper or at meetings, because the president would make better decisions if he were given good information.
Kelly’s diagnosis seems perfectly logical, but others have tried it too, and they have failed to tame Trump by tracking his media consumption.
President Trump’s relationship with television dates back decades, and even now that he is in the White House, his TV viewing habits have not disappeared.
"If candidate Trump was upset about the dishonest media coverage, it was worth showing him that he was also honestly featured in the affected publications," former campaign advisor Sam Nunberg told the Politico in February.
At the time, Tara Palmeri wrote that “six former campaign workers said that the key to controlling Trump’s Twitter habits is to ensure that his personal media consumption includes a steady hymn of praise.”
All right. Okay.
But the idea that Trump’s habits of using Twitter have once been “under control” is ridiculous.
Perhaps these campaigners know something the rest of us don’t know that Trump’s tweets would have been even more inflammatory without their intervention.
We’ll probably never know about tweets that Trump didn’t post.
If his assistants were able to save him from trouble at least a few times, their efforts were worth it.
But no one has been able to prevent Trump from constantly causing controversy.
Part of the problem is that in the White House, which is made up of competing cliques, people are exclusively trying to advance their own interests by providing Trump with material that supports their worldviews, but may not always be reliable.
Politico, which reflects the whole story, wrote in May about the tendency of the advisors to provide the president with information of strategically questionable value.
One of the examples described by reporter Shane Goldmacher is as follows:
"Current and former Trump subordinates say Trump may react to negative press, especially damaging information leaks, explosively, obsessing with finding their source.
This was the case at the end of February, when someone happily gave the president a printed copy of an article on the internet-provocator Charles C. Johnson’s GotNews.com website that accused Deputy Chief of Staff Katie Walsh of being the White House’s “source of multiple information leaks.”
It doesn’t matter whether Johnson has been permanently blocked from Twitter because of mockery, or that he didn’t offer any concrete evidence, or that he has also made false accusations and withdrawn them in the past.
Trump read the article and began asking his subordinates about Walsh.
Goldmacher added that Reince Priebus, then chief of staff, and Rob Porter, head of the White House office, “have tried to establish a system for managing and documenting documents reaching Trump.”
How did you do that?
Kelly tries to do exactly the same thing three months later.
He may prove to be a more effective leader than Priebus, but Trump is still impulsive and his assistants are still competing for influence.
These immutable factors make Kelly's mission very difficult.
