Eesti Pank bought bonds for <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>149 million in July as part of the euro area central banks’ public sector asset purchase programme, while the central bank’s bond portfolio increased to <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>4.36 billion.
The central bank does not disclose more detailed information about purchases.
In reply to the interpellation of members of the Riigikogu, the Governor of the Bank of Estonia, Hardo Hansson, has previously explained that the Eurosystem’s central banks’ asset purchase programme includes three different purchase programmes: covered bonds of the financial sector, asset-backed bonds (ABS) and public sector bonds (PSPP).
The central bank is buying bonds from the market to encourage investors who have sold bonds to invest elsewhere.
The effect of purchases is to reduce the return on lower-risk assets and to motivate investors to take higher risks.
As a general rule, each central bank purchases its own national government bonds in the context of the public sector bond purchase programme, while other sovereign bonds are not purchased.
Since the Estonian state has not issued bonds, Eesti Pank makes so-called replacement purchases within the amount allocated to them.
Replacement purchases are also made by central banks in countries where the supply of covered bonds is limited.
According to Hansson, Eesti Pank generally buys bonds from European institutions, such as bonds from the European Financial Stability Facility and the European Investment Bank.
Eesti Pank will purchase bonds as part of the asset purchase programme as of March 2015.
In the meantime, Elering bonds were also purchased, but Eesti Pank will no longer buy Elering bonds as of June 2016.
As of June, both Elering and Eesti Energia bonds will be purchased by the Finnish Central Bank on behalf of the central banks of the euro area.
