The murder of a journalist highlights the growing threat in Mexico
Weekly Riodoce staff usually gather on Wednesdays to review plans to cover the most recent chaos in the state of Sinaloa, sown by organized crime, corrupt officials, and endless drug warfare.
But today they have gathered under the guise of a personal tragedy to discuss their own safety.
They are told that it is important to change their routines.
Two senior writers discuss which seems safer: to take the children with them to the office that was the target of the 2009 grenade attack, or to leave them at home.
Security experts have written three words on the board at the head of the room: "enemies", "neutral", "allies".
They ask reporters for names in each column to provide evidence no need, impressions and intuition are enough.
Drug traffickers, politicians, businessmen and journalists are suspected of being employed by the government or cartels, along with a list of villains who make it dangerous to portray the chaos in Mexico.
According to the Committee for the Protection of Journalists, the greater the number of bodies that are accumulating across the country, the greater the number of journalists since the inauguration of President Enrique Pena Nieto in December 2012, at least 25,589 journalists have been under state protection after the attacks and threats, and at least seven journalists in seven parts of the country have been killed this year.
Among the dead is their editor and source of inspiration, Riodoce co-founder Javier Valdez Cardenas.
"The biggest mistake is living in Mexico and being a journalist," Valdez wrote in one of his many books on drug violence.
His absence is deeply felt, although his presence can be perceived everywhere on the façade of the Riodoce building, with a large picture of Valdez showing the middle finger with the inscription "Justice" and two 30s reporters, Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez, wearing T-shirts depicting his smiling face with glasses or his characteristic panama hat.
The meeting takes place less than two months after his death. Reporters discuss the common trauma, their nightmares, insomnia, paranoia.
Although a separate state prosecutor's office was set up in 2010 to deal with journalists' cases, according to the Committee for the Protection of Journalists, only two cases have been prosecuted.
As with most annual murders related to drug trafficking and organised crime, which reach thousands, journalist killers rarely come to justice.
The Riodoce editorial continues to reflect on the violence in Sinaloa, even though their hearts are broken and the landscape is now even more dangerous.
Without the killer's data and justice, the security meeting won't be of much use, Ibarra said.
"It's very stupid to waste your time in this meeting," he says.
"Until the cause is known, you will mistrust everyone."
Valdez left the Riodoce office in Culiacan on May 15th.
He managed to drive only a few blocks before two men stopped his red Toyota Corolla. He was forced out of the car and shot 12 times. This is presumably due to the name of the newspaper, which translates as "the twelfth river".
An armed man drove off in Valdez's car and crashed it nearby.
Valdez was 50 years old.
He left behind a wife and two grown children.
Rumors spread freely in Culiacan.
However, on the subject of Valdez, there is mainly silence.
Since Guzman’s arrest last year and extradition to the United States in January, Sinaloa has been one of the country’s bloodiest battlefields as rival clicks fight to fill a power vacuum.
It doesn’t matter if the streets of Sinaloa are shot every day by a few or even several people, or if the cemetery is filled with abundance of decorated double-kings mausoleums that are larger than the homes of many living people.
Let us forget for a moment that peacetime implies that there is only one cartel running a coastal state with valuable ports and drug routes to the United States.
Despite all of this and the fact that Valdez was fully aware of the dangers of his work, Riodoce’s co-founder and manager, Ismail Bojorquez (60), feels immense remorse that he was unable to protect his friend.
He believes that two mistakes contributed to the killing.
The first was the publication in February of an interview with Damaso Lopez, who was a clicker of a cartel competing with Guzman’s sons and at war.
This piece of writing may have aroused the sons by suspected gang members who bought all the copies of the publication as soon as they arrived at the newspaper kiosks.
Another mistake was that Valdez was not forced to leave the country for his own safety after a raid took place in another newspaper editorial covering the same story.
Valdez was a legend both in Mexico and abroad, and his killing is seen as a turning point in the violence against journalists in Mexico.
He had survived so long that his friends and colleagues assumed that he would be there forever.
He worked as a veteran reporter for the Noroeste newspaper in 2003 when he joined five colleagues to create Riodoce, selling <0x24>50 shares.
Bojorquez said it was "impossible to deal with the press in Sinaloa without touching the drug problem."
Over time, the newspaper gained fame with its bold and honest coverage, and sales and advertising grew.
The reporters enjoyed publishing vigorous research without fear of censorship, and readers were fascinated by the print, from which they could read stories that no one else dared to cover.
Eight years after the founding of Riodoce, the newspaper won the prestigious Maria Moors Cabot Prize for its repertoire in Latin America.
In the same year, Valdez won the International Press Freedom Award from the Committee for the Protection of Journalists (AKK) for his courage to follow Mexican drug history wherever it leads.
He frankly admitted that he was afraid.
"I want to live on," he said when accepting the AKK award.
Last October, in an interview with Rompeviento TV, he said that drug trafficking is a way of life in Sinaloa.
“You have to accept the task that comes with being a journalist is another way to play dumb.
I don’t want to be asked what I did in the face of so many deaths or why I didn’t tell you what was going on.”
The Riodoce collective misses Valdez, the joker who snitched like a sailor, the friend who kindly gave hugs and advice, the teacher who knew how to survive.
They relied on his routine.
He always wore his hat.
He went from the office to the El Guayabo bar across the street and always sat at the same table.
Now they ask if his routine love became fatal for him.
His death has also led them to question themselves as to how best to do their work and survive.
“They don’t like it when you mess with their wives, their children, their legitimate businesses, their secret landing sites used to transport drugs.”
"These things should not be touched," said Bojorquez.
The result is strong self-censorship and self-maintenance even in the best times.
Trust your instincts.
If it smells suspicious, stay away.
According to Riodoce editor Andres Villarreal, the problem is that “the sense of smell can be deceived... and that’s what happened to Javier.”
He and others say Sinaloa no longer has the old rules, just as they do in Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Guerrero and other states that are home to a toxic mix of lucrative smuggling routes, weak institutions and corrupt state officials.
The landscape is constantly changing.
In the room where Riodoce staff met for security training, mobile phones were suddenly no longer allowed; a few days before that, it was revealed that spyware sold only to governments had been used to track journalists and activists in Mexico.
In front of the house, two police officers were looking for relief from the 40-degree heat under a tree.
The government appointed them to guard the Riodoce office, located in a four-storey building in the Culiacan middle-class neighborhood.
Some reporters wondered, half-jokingly, whether these police officers were among the 50 percent of police officers the governor himself has labeled unreliable.
Several months have passed since reporters have travelled to mountainous countryside, where de facto drug gangs control.
Riodoce’s edition of this week covered three main stories.
One of them was the murder of the brother of former boxing legend Julio Cesar Chavez in Sinaloa.
In addition, they had a revealing story about spending government money on the governor’s hometown.
And a group of people were kidnapped from one of the most expensive restaurants in Culiacan, a block from the prosecutor's office.
There was no official announcement about who was kidnapped or how it happened, so it was time to be careful when writing what everyone in the city knows the restaurant is a favorite place for both drug dealers and the authorities.
The reporter learned from public records that the restaurant was registered in the name of a politician who belonged to the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party (IRP), which dominated all levels of politics for almost the entire last century.
Recently, several IRP governors have been accused of corruption in widespread cases.
Villarreal asked the reporter to write about previous incidents in the same place, including how Guzman's son, nicknamed El Chapo, escaped from a military raid.
Just a few months earlier, readers would have searched Valdez's column to get information about the kidnapping from the best sources.
"We'd have known before what happened," said 46-year-old Villarreal, whose sleek physique has earned him the nickname El Flaco.
"Now all channels of communication with our sources have been interrupted."
Valdez's office has become a storage room for labels and stickers protesting the killing of journalists, and editorial staff have become something they never expected activists to do on behalf of the press.
Reporter Miriam Ramirez grabbed a few signs and headed the next morning to the prosecutor’s office for a demonstration about another journalist.
Salvador Adame disappeared in Michoacan three days after Valdez was killed.
A burnt body was found and officials say it belongs to him based on DNA tests.
Journalists all over the country have become louder and are scolding the phrase "SOS press" as an organized protest against walkways and buildings.
On this day, President Bojorquez is in Washington, D.C., trying to mobilise international support for justice in the Valdez case.
The day after Valdez's death in a meeting with the governor of Sinaloa, Ramirez accused the authorities of spying on journalists and killing them for telling the truth.
After that, he asked that he be redirected from the government's activities, worrying that hatred had affected his objectivity.
Valdez had repeatedly said that Mexican journalists were "limited" by organized crime, complicit state officials, and an indifferent society.
In his latest book, Drug Journalism, he wrote that reporters are not only killed by drug gangs, but also by orders of politicians and security forces who are affiliated with organised crime.
Last year, the media monitoring group Articulo 19 attributed more than half of the attacks on journalists to police and state officials.
"You will die in Mexico because they want you to be silenced," Ramirez said.
The murders are obviously blood-staining.
No one will forget the death of blogger Maria Elizabeth Macias in Tamaulipas, a northern border state, six years ago.
His body was found with a letter, probably signed by the Los Zetas cartel, saying, "I'm here for my reports."
A computer keyboard and headphones lay next to his cut-off head.
Some publications have decided to close their doors, such as the newspaper El Norte in the northern border state of Chihuahua after their correspondent Miroslava Breach was killed in March.
Others continue to do what the newspaper El Manana de Nuevo Laredo did after their leader was murdered in 2004.
In 2010, the newspaper Diario de Ciudad Juarez publicly addressed the drug cartels with an editorial on the front page entitled "What do you want from us?".
Some journalists have fled their home states or even the country.
This is a nerve-wracking decision.
It is difficult to find work in exile and they still have to hide in the streets to avoid dangers.
And sometimes they are being chased, as probably happened to photographer Ruben Espinosa, who was murdered along with four women in a Mexican apartment in 2015, three months after fleeing Veracruz.
Those who stay put and continue to work have to dance around risky decisions every day.
Ibarra, who once wanted to become a poet, admits that her coverage of the drug business scares her.
"Mexico is on its way to hell, and that's why I became a reporter," he said.
On a recent Friday at midnight, when the latest number was already locked, Riodoce editors were sitting on the sidewalk in front of the office, drinking beer when everyone’s phones suddenly began to vibrate.
In the coastal resort town of Mazatlan, 19 people were reportedly killed in shootings between rival gangs and security forces.
The war continued to escalate, as promised by several messages left by cartels found in the area.
From the sidewalk, reporters posted the news on the Riodoce website using a mobile phone.
The next day, I needed a change.
Sirens were blazing along another shooting in the area.
Bojorquez peeked at the police officers on guard to see if they were on guard.
If they were afraid, at least they didn't show it.
Under the massive portrait of the fallen founder of the newspaper, on which his middle finger can be seen all over Sinaloa, Riodoce’s employees edited his footsteps.
"How could you even think of closure," Bojorquez said, "if on the same day that Javier was killed, an apprentice asked me to send him out to the streets for a report?"
Dinosaur uses protective color to avoid enemies
At first glance, it looks like a statue, albeit quite frightening.
Scientists have now revealed the first discoveries of an incredible rhino-sized creature discovered by a Canadian miner, so well preserved that experts have described it as "the Mona Lisa of the dinosaurs."
It was so well preserved that it was even possible to detect that his skin covered with armor was of a reddish-brown color, and his past had been somewhat "complex".
A report published in Current Biology described the creature as "the best-preserved armored dinosaur ever found" and "one of the best dinosaurs in the world."
The fossil is a new species of nodosaurus that lived in the middle of the Cretaceous, 110-112 million years ago.
Its incredibly good preservation stunned researchers who describe it as "really remarkable."
According to National Geographic, this equation-covered vegetarian is the best preserved type of fossil ever found.
It was discovered by Shawn Funk on March 21, 2011, when he was mining at the Suncor Millenium mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada.
He hit something that did not resemble the surrounding stone, and decided to look more closely.
The fossil was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
For the next six years, they worked to excavate the animal from a 2,500-pound (1,100-pound) plot of land.
After all this hard work, the final result is now finally ready for public disclosure.
"If you tweak your eyes a little, you can almost believe he's asleep," said lead author Caleb Brown, a researcher at the Royal Tyrrell Museum where the creature is exhibited.
"It goes into the history of science as one of the most beautiful and best-preserved dinosaurs - the Mona Lisa of dinosaurs."
While examining his skin, scientists found that this herbivore, though covered in armor and reminiscent of a walking tank, was likely significantly endangered by carnivorous dinosaurs.
This largely armored dinosaur used red and white protective colors to hide from predators, and used a sheltering technique called counter-shadow, which is also used by many modern animals.
According to experts, this allowed the dinosaur to better blend in with its surroundings and avoid enemies, as larger dinosaurs were likely hunting him.
This 110-million-year-old nodosaurian creature first came to the news in May and is now available for visit at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
Scientists have now studied the creature and named it after Mark Mitchell, a laboratory worker at the Borealopelta markmitchell museum, who was part of a team that spent more than 7,000 hours exposing the animal to the painstaking discovery.
Thanks to the amazingly good preservation of the specimen, Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists were able to document the shape and size of the armor on the animal's body.
They discovered a counter-eclipsing, a conservation method common in the animal kingdom, meaning that the upper half of the creature was darker than the lower half.
Although the counter-shadow is widespread, the findings come as a surprise, as the Borealopetta is much larger than the animals that live in shadow today.
This suggests that the dinosaur was sufficiently actively hunted by other carnivorous dinosaurs, that evolution preferred to hide as a survival tactic rather than confrontation.
However, most modern counter-eclipsing animals, such as deer, zebras, or armadillos, are much smaller and more vulnerable to prey, suggesting that nodosaurus had to make a real effort to survive.
"The vigorous hunting of a huge dinosaur covered in armor shows just how dangerous dinosaur predators from the Cretaceous could be," Brown said.
Chemical analysis of the organic compounds in the armours also revealed that the skin of the dinosaur was reddish-brown.
Scientists continue to investigate the animal to get clues about its life, including the remaining contents of its intestines, to find out what the animal ate as its last meal.
They believe that the dinosaur fell dead into the river, thus flowing into the sea, where he sank to the bottom of the ocean.
At that time, Alberta was as warm as it is now in southern Florida, and the rivers and oceans were likely much further inland than they are now.
"This nodosaurus is truly remarkable because it is fully covered with the preserved scaled skin, while it has also remained three-dimensional, preserving the animal's original shape," Brown said.
As a result, the animal looks almost the same today as it did in the Cretaceous.
You don’t have to use a lot of imagination to reconstruct it – it’s enough to squeeze your eyes and it feels like you’re asleep.”
The Cretaceous era was a time when huge bipedal carnivorous dinosaurs roamed the Earth—theropods.
Although the king of all of them, Tyrannosaurus rex, lived millions of years later than Borealopetta, this armored dinosaur may have been hunted by some of its fearsome predecessors.
These include Acrocanthosaurus, a 38-foot (11.5 meters) tall monster and a six-ton-weight monster.
Scientists, whose recent findings have been published in the journal Current Biology, believe that Borealopella was washed into the sea after death and mummified in mud.
The creature was discovered by Shawn Funk on March 21, 2011, when he was mining at the Millenium mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada.
According to the museum, it is the best preserved armored dinosaur in the world, including skin and scales, and is complete from the cone to the hips.
These creatures were on average 18 feet (five meters) tall and weighed up to 3,000 pounds (1300 kg).
Two 20-inch-long spikes burst out of its shoulders.
Scientists believe that this armored herbivore traveled through what is now Western Canada until a flooded river washed into its open sea.
But the dinosaur’s undersea burial site helped preserve its scales in fine detail.
The fossilized remains of this particular specimen are so well preserved that the skin remains still cover the skulls of the dinosaur along the crippled armour plates.
As Michael Greshko wrote in National Geographic: “This degree of preservation is as rare as winning the lottery.
The more I look at it, the more unbelievable it feels.
The petrified skin remains still cover the bumpy armor plates on the skull of the animal.
The right forefoot lies next to him, and the five toes are stretched upwards.
I can count the armor on his sole."
How did one activist find the answer to the question “Whose Streets?”
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell was in shock.
Just a day after traveling to New York City, this St. Louis resident sat on a bed in a rented room via Airbnb, browsing Facebook on his phone.
He came across a post from his former schoolmate.
It said, "The police just killed an 18-year-old and he's still lying on the street."
He was confused why no one else had posted this information on his stream, so he shut down Facebook and opened Twitter.
<0x40>TheePharoah’s posts were repeatedly shared on his timeline.
A rapper from the St. Louis area broadcast a live tweet about the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed 18-year-old black young man who was killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He posted a picture of Brown's lifeless body lying on the street, staying there for four hours.
"That's crazy," Ferrell thought to himself.
But death was nothing new for him or his community.
He put his phone away, but later that night he saw tweets that reported people gathering on Canfield Drive this time.
They shared photos of a police tape and screaming people and a man who claimed to be Brown's father and kept a sign saying, "Ferguson police just killed my unarmed son!"
He watched a live stream of a policeman standing in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In the second video, another policeman said he tipped a gun and yelled, “I’m going to kill all of you...animals.”
Ferrell remembers how he caught himself thinking, "This is unusual."
"It's not the kind of murder we're used to, and we could call it typical."
I felt scared at that moment.
I was angry and crying.”
He booked a return flight and went home the next day.
When he landed at 11 p.m., he went to his father’s to pick up his six-year-old daughter and decided that the next morning they would go alone to Ferguson.
What happened with Ferrell and Ferguson over the next three years is a central theme in the new documentary, Whose Streets?, which premieres in cinemas on August 11.
It’s a story of survival and protest, of love and loss, of strength and resilience from the perspective of those who live in this community and who filled the streets with demanding answers.
When Ferrell and his daughter, wearing a floral dress and a matching crown on their head, drove to Ferguson, they again discussed the experiences and living conditions of blacks, which had been repeatedly discussed before this morning.
“Remember when I taught you how the black community had to fight for its rights?” she recalls asking herself.
"We're going to Ferguson right now because the police killed an 18-year-old boy, and that's not right."
"I couldn't take him with me," Ferrell said later.
“What’s happening now is the culmination of what’s happened in the past.
He needs to know it and see it and grow in it.
He must learn about activism and organization, but also know the different layers of black experience and living conditions, and what we must do to become free and free ourselves.
Even if I manage to raise him without personally experiencing blatant racism, he is no different from any other black girl.
I feel like I would do him a terrible service if I protected him from this world.”
The first stop they made when they reached Ferguson was on South Florissant, a place across the street from the police station that had become a sort of campground where activists were waiting for news of a police officer named Darren Wilson, who was never charged.
There, Ferrell and his daughter joined forces with a local business owner who prepared lunch.
They put together food bags and helped distribute them to the protesters.
For Ferrell, a new type of activism slowly began to take shape.
"My activism changed completely after August 9," he said, noting that when he was a student at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, he was president of the Union of Minority Nursing Students and focused on food justice and health-related inequalities in black communities.
“I didn’t have any organizational experience.
It's all just settled."
Weeks later, during an evening demonstration, Ferrell met one of the film’s co-directors, Sabah Folayan.
Folayan said he and filmmaker Lucas Alvarado-Farrar were simply trying to document what was happening.
Ferrelli wondered, “Are you trying to document what’s happening, or are you trying to find a story that can be exploited?”
This skepticism was due to the countless instances of people, often white, coming into the community and trying to take advantage of its pain and resilience.
Folayan explained in a recent interview: “We had heard that the voices of people born and raised in Ferguson were not heard and we wanted to do it differently.”
Folayan had already shaken hands with co-director Damon Davis, an artist in the area known for his activism in connection with death row prisoners.
His involvement made the project appealing to Ferrell and six other locals who were watched by the team in Whose Streets? for years after Brown was shot.
"In this documentary, no one speaks for us or for us, we speak for ourselves," Davis said.
"It was important to me how these people were depicted, because that's how I'm depicted."
Although the goal was not to focus on Ferrell's experience -- to show that the movement was not "a redeemer's guide, but a community gathering," as Folayan said -- he became the most open actor in the film.
As a result, "Whose Streets?" documents surprisingly personal aspects of Ferrell's life, such as falling in love and marrying his wife.
"I felt like I was naked," Ferrell said, laughing at the first time he saw a finished linen work.
“But I realized that doing this work and humanizing black people must be accompanied by a certain vulnerability.”
What’s more, Ferrell’s story emphasizes and re-focuses the role of a black homosexual woman in the wider Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the three instigators of the movement who posted the theme <0x23>BlackLivesMatter on social media after the 2012 murder of black teenager Trayvon Martin are homosexual.
"Black gay women in the leading role have generally sustained the movement," Ferrell said, "and this is precisely because we have to constantly fight on many fronts.
“Black homosexual women must bear all this burden.”
Folayan agreed, noting that "the movement is indeed kept alive by black women, and many of them are black homosexual women."
At the same time, he argues that "there is no such thing as creating equal opportunities" - Ferrelli was not chosen as the centerpiece of the film because of his identity.
"He was the person who was blowing the right energy out of him," he said.
“But it’s not a coincidence that she was right on the front line, because living as a black homosexual woman at such junctions is a lot at stake.
Its energy can be perceived through the screen.”
Meanwhile, news cameras from Ferguson have long since disappeared, but racial ties between the community and the police are still fragile.
During the demonstration, Ferrelli was sentenced to two-and-a-half years of probation for blocking the road.
He describes the socio-political climate in the region he calls home simply as a “smooth boom.”
Nevertheless, he still holds the importance of the mantra he has etched in his memory since he went to the streets of Ferguson three years ago.
“It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We need to love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose but our chains.”
