The rules for handling genetically modified crops must be clear
The Ministry of Rural Affairs sent the Bill on Amendments to the Genetically Modified Organisms Release into the Environment (GMOVS) Act and the Plant Protection Act to the approval circle.
The amendment to the Act will refrain from creating a separate database for the locations of genetically modified (GM) crops as well as for operators, for this purpose the plant health register will be used in the future.
In addition, the obligation of the GM crop operator to have a prior agreement with a person engaged in beekeeping within the prescribed radius will be amended.
Although genetically modified crops are not currently grown in Estonia, we consider it necessary to have clear rules for the coexistence of genetically modified and non-genetically modified crops.
At least until the decision has been made to declare Estonia GMO-free,” said Sigmar Suu, Head of Plant Health Department at the Ministry of Rural Affairs.
"At the same time, it must be taken into account that the measures developed must be targeted and proportionate, taking into account the costs and administrative burdens for both the private and public sectors," added Suu.
The Bill repeals the provisions of the GMOVS relating to the database of locations and handlers of GM crops and the training on handling, establishes the requirements for handling GM crops and the commencement of economic activities.
In the specific case of beekeeping, the current obligation for GM crop growers to inform beekeepers of the start of GM crop cultivation will be replaced by an obligation to reach an appropriate agreement with the beekeeper before starting cultivation.
The Bill has been sent to the ministries for coordination.
All interested parties have the opportunity to examine it in the information system of the Bills and, if they wish, to submit their opinions to the Ministry of Rural Affairs.
The planned changes will primarily affect persons active in the field of plant production, beekeepers and the Agricultural Board.
In the European Union, including Estonia, only one GM crop is allowed to grow - maize MON 810.
So far, however, no Estonian farmer has been interested in cultivating GM crops.
This is due to the fact that in Estonia there is no corn pest, European stalk, against which the MON 810 maize line is resistant.
Also, the varieties of this maize line are bred in the southern regions, and this maize is not suitable for our climatic conditions.
In 2015 and 2016, the Ministry of Rural Affairs commissioned studies to detect possible contamination by GM organisms in the seeds of different varieties of summer rape, corn and soya grown in Estonia.
The results of the analysis of the samples showed that the seeds did not contain foreign genes and the results of the study concluded that the seeds of the varieties of rape, corn and soya grown in Estonia do not contain genetically modified organisms.
It can be inferred from the above that no GM crops are deliberately grown in Estonia, and it has also been confirmed that no accidental contamination has occurred.
