Drinking alcohol is equivalent to “training” the brain.
According to Livestrong, Dr. Gordon Sheperd is such a wine fan that he believes that wine can train the brain better than anything else in the world.
Sheperd is a neuroscientist at Yale University.
“It’s not about alcohol or how it affects our feelings and thoughts, it’s about the “very active” process of tasting wine.
By smelling the glass, swirling the wine in our mouths, enjoying it and sensing aftertaste, we put our brains to work to create a taste for wine.
According to Sheperd, wine molecules don’t actually contain flavor, but taste comes from the way wine stimulates the brain.
He compares how the brain "sees" colors.
"The taste is not in wine, the taste creates the taster of wine," says Sheperd.
Other things that influence the taste of wine are, for example, our age, gender, and even the amount of saliva that a person produces.
Shepherd, of course, warns that wine is not meant to get drunk.
“There has to be more,” he says.
If you drink too much, the system will be oversaturated.
Excessive wine drinking can harm the brain instead of benefiting – a 2004 study found that people who drink more than three glasses of wine risk loss of memory, loss of balance, and reduced mental capacity.
