From the Philippines to the heart of fashion fans
Shoulder-woven bags are a summer classic, which in recent years has become a hit product in its own right, which a true summer enthusiast must even hang on his arm, and on which merchants have been able to weld a price tag suitable for a hit, despite its modest origin.
A shoulder-woven bag is probably one of the things that has existed in everyone’s life and the possession of which has not caused any special emotions.
It's just there, and if it's not, then nothing's broken.
But now the straw bags are making a real triumph, and fashion fans have replaced their exquisite designer bags with simple straw-woven bags for the summer months.
It’s not just a beach bag, it’s just as popular today as a street bag, and more courageous women even walk into the office with it.
Here, however, it is worth clarifying beforehand whether a summer look like this is still sitting on the boss or whether it is worth pushing the pine and laptop to a somewhat more formal sumada.
Variety has made straw bags a true summer love for women.
For example, when reading foreign fashion blogs, the first thing you notice is that fashion gourmets rush to the local market as the first thing on a holiday trip and buy themselves some straw bags, to which they will be faithful throughout the holiday period, which will accompany you on the beach, on the market and also hanging out with friends in the city.
Some bloggers are so generous that they buy a lot of bags on the market and sell them or give them away to their loyal readers.
It is worth noting that the demand for bags among readers is so high that in the real world, women (and men!) would probably go hand in hand to become the happy owner of a bag.
In some ways, this madness is understandable, as it is rare that in the fashion world it is possible to buy something that has become a hit for just a few dozen euros.
True, clever merchants have also discovered a simple way to make money here, and so the finer luxury brands sell straw bags for a few hundred and thousands of euros.
Probably so that the richer customers don’t feel like mere mortals who walk around with some cheap bags.
For example, you can buy a Dolce & Gabbana shoulder bag for over <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1,000.
For Chanel’s interpretation of the shoulder bag, however, it is worth around <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>6,000.
Unlike most fashion designers, straw bags do not come from some big fashionable ones, but their story began farther away.
It is said that straw bags originated in the far Philippines, where they have been widely transported.
Weaving shoulder bags there is primarily an export trade and the locals are not often seen walking around with them.
It is said that the straw weaving technique dates back to the 14th century and is quite similar to ordinary basket weaving.
However, since the shoulder bag does not need to be woven as hard as the basket, patterns and other materials can be woven into them, which make the bag more personal and therefore more attractive.
For example, recently there have been especially trendy bags with colored ribbons or leather strips in them.
A thank you letter can be sent to actress Jane Birkin, whose biggest weaved shoulder bag fan has never been seen before.
In fact, he matched the shoulder bag with all kinds of clothing sets and didn’t even want to go to the Cannes Film Festival with it.
The popularity of these bags is not less important nowadays, but the fact that taking care of them is the head of a rooster and unlike many other Sudanese people, they do not have to be cared for with special tools, but water and a wet towel do the same.
As always, brands have come up with all kinds of interpretations in addition to the classic look.
For example, if you wish, you can buy a ribbon wrapped with straw or a tiny shoulder bag.
At the same time, it is worth remembering that a classic shoulder bag never goes out of fashion, but on the shoulder bag it does.
What is a classic shoulder bag?
For centuries it has been regarded as a classical bag, which resembles a basket in its style, is open on the top and has shorts, as well as handles made of straw.
5 Healthy Ice Creams to Make at Home
Lifehack.org outlined ways to make different types of ice cream at home that contain fewer calories than shop ice creams.
Lemon and butter ice cream - whisk the lemon juice with sugar in a large bowl, add the butter and whipped cream and mix everything to an even mass, put the mixture in the refrigerator.
Chocolate and nut butter ice cream - blended Greek yogurt, frozen bananas, cocoa powder and maple syrup into an even mass.
Then add a little peanut butter and blend the mixture for a few seconds.
Ice cream is ready to be eaten.
Peach ice cream - mix in a bowl of non-fat milk, sugar substitute, egg, frozen or ordinary peach slices and almond extract to form an even mass and place the resulting mixture in the refrigerator.
Coconut ice cream - blend coconut milk, coconut flakes, vanilla extract, maple syrup and frozen bananas and place the resulting mixture in the refrigerator.
Banana ice cream - mix the frozen banana pieces in a bowl with low-fat milk to a uniform mass, serve with nuts and consume immediately.
